		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2009"></a><br><code>sle2009/paper14</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Natural and Flexible Error Recovery for Generated Parsers</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MaartjedeJonge.html">Maartje de Jonge</a>, <a href="../profile/EmmaNilssonNyman.html">Emma Nilsson-Nyman</a>, <a href="../profile/LennartCLKats.html">Lennart C. L. Kats</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_16">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_16</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It improves generated parser tooling by adding better, more robust error recovery.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> Error recovery aims to improve user experience by producing more helpful behavior/messages when parsing fails.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> Parser behavior at runtime (recovery strategy) is a key part of the execution model of generated parsers.
</li></ul></li></ul>
